article.headline: Vandy back for third time in four years
article.linkText: Vanderbilt upsets LSU, sets up 5 vs. 6 SEC title game
article.story:
NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Vanderbilt Commodores love a strong
start, and they rolled right over the defending Southeastern
Conference tournament champions Saturday night.

Jenni Benningfield scored 20 points, and (No. 21 AP) Vanderbilt
knocked off (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP) LSU 78-66 in the SEC tournament semifinals to reach the title game for the third time in four years.

"We came out very confident and mentally ready to play tonight
just like we have in the last couple of games in this tournament,"
Vanderbilt coach Melanie Balcomb said. "We get off to a good
start, and it just really helps us."

The second-seeded Lady Tigers had been trying to reach the title
game for the third straight year, hoping to add a third tournament
championship to their resume.

But the SEC's best shooting team couldn't match sixth-seeded
Vanderbilt (23-7), which won its seventh straight game by
outperforming the Lady Tigers -- against whom they began their
streak with a 61-55 win at Baton Rouge on Feb. 19.

LSU acting coach Pokey Chatman said she had several reasons for
the loss ranging from the semifinal loss of Vanderbilt's instate
rival Tennessee earlier Saturday to the Commodores playing a couple
miles from their campus.

"How much time do you have?" she said.

Seimone Augustus led LSU (23-7) with 22 points.

The SEC now is guaranteed of getting only its second-ever
champion to win four games in four days, as Auburn did in 1997. The
Commodores will play No. 20 Georgia, a 68-66 overtime upset winner
over top-ranked Tennessee, for the title Sunday.

"We have to suck it up tomorrow whether we're tired or not,"
Benningfield said.

The Commodores are looking for their fourth tournament title and
first since 2002 when they won on this very court. Balcomb credited
the surge with how they survived a season in which Abi Ramsey was
suspended following a drunken driving arrest and a handful of
injuries including stress fractures for both Benningfield and point
guard Dee Davis.

"We remained positive, and I think we really persevered through
this and I think it's paying off for us now," Balcomb said.

Carla Thomas added 12 points, Ramsey 11 and Hillary Hager and
Ashley Earley 10 apiece for Vanderbilt. The Commodores outrebounded
LSU 44-28 and outshot them 46.6 percent (27-of-58) to 38.6 percent
(22-of-57).

LSU and Vandy were the SEC's top teams in field-goal percentage,
but the Lady Tigers led just once -- after the opening basket by
Hanna Biernacka.

Ramsey hit a 3-pointer that started the Commodores rolling, and
they hit seven of their first 11 shots and led 18-9 with 12:03 to
go on a pair of free throws by Dee Davis. Vandy led 45-30 at
halftime and by as much as 52-34 on a three-point play by Ramsey
with 17:35 left.

"Ten-foot hole, nine-foot ladder, and that's the story of the
game," Chatman said.

Augustus and Temeeka Johnson tried to rally the Lady Tigers.
Johnson, shut out in the first half, scored 11 points, and Augustus
had 14 in the second half. But the closest they got was 65-60 on a
pair of free throws by Scholanda Hoston with 5:56 left.

"It was too big of a hole for us to come back at the end,"
Augustus said.

Vandy answered with six straight free throws by Earley, Katie
Antony and Ramsey to pad the victory.

Hoston finished with 12 points. LSU's Doneeka Hodges had just
nine points on 3-of-10 shooting. She averaged 14.9 during the
regular season.
